Discovery of The Synergistic Dual-payload Antibody-Drug Conjugate(CTPH-02) by Combination of
MMAE and Novel Payloads
Myeong Joo Kim, Da Hyun Kim, Soyeon Lim, Jiwoo Lee, Eunseok Choi, Wonbin Ha, Han ah Kim, Jaebeom Park, Seung Chan Kim, Chang-Sun Lee*
Celltrion Pharm, Inc., Incheon, Republic of Korea
Introduction for dual-payload ADC
Abstract No. : 6597
Background
The greatest promise of ADC is that it can minimize side effects on normal tissues through
the cancer-selective delivery of drugs. However, unanswered problems such as ADC
aggregation, premature cleavage of payloads, and insufficient MTD still hamper the road for
ADC to become a major anticancer treatment option. Although most ADC research has
been focused on novel conjugation methods and hydrophilic linkers, many ADC drugs in
clinical trials have still underperformed due to the dose-limiting toxicity. Despite
acknowledging that ADC’s DLT is mainly from the payload used, research efforts on
discovering novel payloads have been relatively limited.

CTPH dual-payload ADCs offer better TI than high DAR single-
payload ADC’s
We discover a class of drugs regulating cell proliferation that provide a synergistic effect
with MMAE in drug combination cytotoxicity studies. Dual-payload ADCs prepared by a few
linker options are as potent as each single-payload ADCs even at lower DAR. Very excitingly,
CTPH dual-payload ADC(CTPH-02) outperform the corresponding high DAR single-payload
ADC’s for cancer cells with low-to-medium antigen expression. CTPH dual-payload ADCs
also perform better than not only high DAR single-payload ADCs but also FDA-approved
ADCs in CDX efficacy model studies. With these findings, CTPH dual-payload ADCs may
have better therapeutic window than typical single-payload ADC’s.
Currently, we are running rodent PK and TK studies to prove if CPTH dual-payload ADCs
may improve toxicity profile compared to high DAR single-payload ADCs. If studies work as
promised, CTPH dual-payload strategy could offer treatment options for cancer patients
with low TPS and IHC scores.

Since the goal of ADC research is to improve the therapeutic window (TI), we have
developed a unique ADC platform technology by adopting a dual-payload concept, from
which we aim to achieve three different goals:
1. Increasing MTD (maximum tolerable dose) as well as lowering
MED (minimum efficacious dose)
2. Better performing cytotoxicity even for low antigen-expressed cancer cells
3. Overcoming resistance acquired from the current cancer therapy by applying
combinatorial MoA (mechanism of action) from different drugs
The newly found drug combination based on a different MoA from one of the known ADC
payloads should show synergistic cytotoxicity, which would improve the therapeutic
window (TI) by increasing MTD and lowering MED.
